In JSON, we will have to escape the backslashes again? Actually when we write the JSON string, backslashes are escape characters. So to represent a single backslash in the JSON string, we need to write \\\\. So the sequence "\\uD800" in the Java source becomes "\\\\uD800" in JSON string. Let's break down:

We want the testcase string to contain the characters: @Test public void nextIndexOfSurrogateInsufficientLength() {\n        CharacterReader r = new CharacterReader("\\uD800");\n        assertEquals(-1, r.nextIndexOf("\\uD800\\uDC00"));\n    }

But in the JSON string, we need to escape double quotes and backslashes. So we replace " with \" and \ with \\\\. So the part `"\\uD800"` becomes `\"\\\\uD800\"`. Similarly for `"\\uD800\\uDC00"` becomes `\"\\\\uD800\\\\uDC00\"`.

Thus the full testcase string for JSON:

"@Test public void nextIndexOfSurrogateInsufficientLength() {\n        CharacterReader r = new CharacterReader(\"\\\\uD800\");\n        assertEquals(-1, r.nextIndexOf(\"\\\\uD800\\\\uDC00\"));\n    }"

We'll do that.

Now, we output the JSON.

We'll have fixed_code as an array with one string, and additional_testcases as array of three objects.

Now, we must ensure we output only the JSON object, no extra text.

Let's write the final output.{
  "fixed_code": [
    "    int nextIndexOf(CharSequence seq) {\n        // doesn't handle scanning for surrogates\n        char startChar = seq.charAt(0);\n        int seqLen = seq.length();\n        for (int offset = pos; offset < length; offset++) {\n            // scan to first instance of startchar:\n            if (startChar != input[offset])\n                while(++offset < length && startChar != input[offset]);\n            if (offset >= length) break;\n            if (offset + seqLen > length) {\n                continue;\n            }\n            int i = offset + 1;\n            int last = i + seqLen - 1;\n            if (offset < length) {\n                for (int j = 1; i < last && seq.charAt(j) == input[i]; i++, j++);\n                if (i == last) // found full sequence\n                    return offset - pos;\n            }\n        }\n        return -1;\n    }"
  ],
  "additional_testcases": [
    {
      "path": "org/jsoup/parser/CharacterReaderTest.java",
      "testcase": "@Test public void nextIndexOfInsufficientLengthImmediate() {\n        CharacterReader r = new CharacterReader(\"ab\");\n        assertEquals(-1, r.nextIndexOf(\"abc\"));\n    }"
    },
    {
      "path": "org/jsoup/parser/CharacterReaderTest.java",
      "testcase": "@Test public void nextIndexOfInsufficientLengthAfterSkip() {\n        CharacterReader r = new CharacterReader(\"xay\");\n        assertEquals(-1, r.nextIndexOf(\"ayz\"));\n    }"
    },
    {
      "path": "org/jsoup/parser/CharacterReaderTest.java",
      "testcase": "@Test public void nextIndexOfSurrogateInsufficientLength() {\n        CharacterReader r = new CharacterReader(\"\\uD800\");\n        assertEquals(-1, r.nextIndexOf(\"\\uD800\\uDC00\"));\n    }"
    }
  ]
}